After a bit of research, it seem to be aÂ known issueÂ when unicode is contained on a String object ([ref|https://www.quora.com/Is-Javas-toLowercase-string-method-reliable-for-Unicode] ),Â String.toLowerCase() would produce a incorrect result.

In this caseÂ "\u0130" would become a String object with three char which are [Â i, Â Ì‡, x] instead of [Â Ä°, x].

So by given a incorrect result from .toLowCase() method,Â StringUtils.replaceIgnoreCase end attempt to access the segment of string which is not exist which is 3 in this case while str.length() is 2.

The fixture I come up with is replacing the .toLowcase() to .toUpperCase() in order to avoid the mis-interprettion on .toLowerCase while performing case-insensitive comparisons.


